description:
Sponsor: Montech HyperFlow 360 Cooler on Amazon https://geni.us/dWBIbF6
The Yeston RX 9070 XT Sakura Sugar Atlantis GPU, which we've shortened to "Waifu" edition, shows the video card design world that not everything has to be a black-and-RGB rectangle. The Atlantis goes for a pink-and-blue gradient on its shroud with an anime character backplate, while also implementing a full flow-through area for the right-most of the three fans. The card has dual VBIOS, an LED switch, and otherwise standard features on the PCB. This review and benchmark of the Yeston RX 9070 XT Atlantis "OC" tests it for thermals, acoustics, and performance vs. the Sapphire RX 9070 XT Pulse, which is supposed to be closer to an MSRP model. We may look at the PowerColor Red Devil next, if there's interest!

Watch our original Yeston Cute Pet RX 580 review! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fGGKaX1D9Zo
And our Cute Pet case review: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=62oPBdI9CSA
Or our RX 7900 XTX Yeston card review: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UeiZhSadtL0

The best way to support our work is through our store: https://store.gamersnexus.net/

Like our content? Please consider becoming our Patron to support us: http://www.patreon.com/gamersnexus

TIMESTAMPS

00:00 - Yeston RX 9070 XT Sakura Sugar Atlantis OC
03:56 - The Marketing
06:17 - Tear Down
09:27 - Cooling Solution
13:00 - Finding the Smell
14:42 - GN Team Smells the Module
18:12 - Thermal Benchmarks
19:47 - Fan Speed vs Thermals
21:03 - Acoustic Testing and Frequency Spectrum
22:45 - Gaming Benchmarks
24:28 - Conclusion

** Please like, comment, and subscribe for more! **

Links to Amazon and Newegg are typically monetized on our channel (affiliate links) and may return a commission of sales to us from the retailer. This is unrelated to the product manufacturer. Any advertisements or sponsorships are disclosed within the video ("this video is brought to you by") and above the fold in the description. We do not ever produce paid content or "sponsored content" (meaning that the content is our idea and is not funded externally aside from whatever ad placement is in the beginning) and we do not ever charge manufacturers for coverage.

comments.text:
Hello, I need help with a recurring issue related to my GPU. Here's a detailed summary of the problem:

GPU Model: AMD Radeon RX 580 8GB (Sapphire Nitro+)

Issue: The GPU randomly loses display output during gaming or even in regular usage. When it happens, the monitor goes black, and the only solution is to restart the PC. After restarting, I sometimes need to reinstall the GPU drivers for it to work again.

Steps I've already tried:

1. Used different versions of AMD drivers (both old and latest).


2. Tried a different RX 580 GPU (same issue occurs).


3. Updated BIOS of the motherboard (Gigabyte B650 DS3H).


4. Clean-installed drivers using DDU (Display Driver Uninstaller).


5. Downgraded Windows from 11 to 10  still the same issue.


6. Performed GPU and PSU stress tests  no immediate crash, but the issue appears randomly later.


7. Checked all power connectors and reseated the GPU multiple times.



System Specs:

CPU: AMD Ryzen 5 7600X

Motherboard: Gigabyte B650 DS3H

RAM: Acer Predator Vesta II DDR5 6000MHz (32GB, 16x2)

Storage: WD Blue SN580 500GB Gen4 NVMe SSD

PSU: Cooler Master MWE Bronze 750 V3 ATX 3.1

Monitor: Acer Nitro VG240Y M3 (using DisplayPort)

Cooler: Arctic Freezer 36 Black



Ive tried almost everything I could, but the problem still persists. I would really appreciate your help or suggestions on how to diagnose this further or solve it permanently. Could this be a compatibility issue with the RX 580 and my AM5 platform? Or is there something I might have missed?

Thank you in advance!

comments.text:
Okay more serious comment. I'm impressed that this meme card actually performs quite well. As for the "fragrance strip" its just like any other air freshener, where you have a highly porous mesh material full of fragrance oils. As the card heats up and moves air over the strip, it will release miniscule amounts of the oils into the air, which are heavily scented. The middle has the plastic sleeve to control the amount of fragrance actually dispersed, as its based on airflow over surface area. I'm curious if the company is willing to stand behind their product and either sell replacement strips or at least provide compatible strip part numbers for those who wish to actually maintain the scent long term. 

I would be curious to see how long this strip actually last for, maybe we could see a long term test of this just running in a corner somewhere, just running 4 hours a day. These strips are usually only good for a few months at most. 

I honestly have to wonder though if this is due to the whole stereotype that weebs don't shower and are allergic to deodorant. Like do we have to resort to making gpus with air fresheners to make man caves smell decent?

comments.text: A possible reason for the fan behavior is that the bios is trying to prevent a potential fan stall and causing the fan to prematurely fail. Forcing the fans to start at a higher speed and then drop down once the fan is guaranteed to be on is much more reliable than encountering a fan stall and then continuously pumping voltage into the fan without it spinning. Technology Connections has a good video on the logic behind it.

I bought a yeston 3080 a few years ago.
1. It lost it's perfume scent about two months, IF THAT, later. I believe it was infused into the plastic or paint of the fan shroud and just cooked off from heat.

3. For the first few years, doing driver updates was iffy. Sometimes it would reboot my PC during the middle of it for no reason. Haven't had that happen with recent gpus from Nvidia

Basically, unless you have NO STOCK ANYWHERE and NEED A GPU; don't bother paying the goon tax. It might work but I'm sure even a Zotac or whatever current "crap tier" partner card is better than this thing.

I think Yeston's RX 6700/7800 Sakura cards are among the best-looking GPUs.  It has a 3-piece 3-color shroud that jagged like snowflakes.   White parts are on top of Blue and purplish parts.  And of course, it's Waifu.  It looks better than this Yeston RX9070.
Of course, these older cards have white PCB too.  I have a white PC case, HYTE Y60 - which means no way of seeing the back of the card, but would really showcase the fans and such.   The Yeston's 6700/7700s were out of my budget and not really easy to come by in the USA back then. 

The only big thing that makes me NOT want to by a Sakura card is the Fragrance "feature" - which some people could be sensitive to.   I think its a neat gimmick, but they really should make it something that can be easily removed.  

I give them big thumbs up for not another bunch of black retangles in our computers.    They do make basic white too.

comments.text:
(Fun?) fact: Yeston "waifu" cards are coined as "wh*re cards" (literal translation should be sow cards) domestically.
Their first "waifu" series coincides with the start of the crypto bubble, and Yeston's notorious pro-miner selling strategy led to most of these waifu cards being sold to crypto miners instead of individual customers. Imagine a waifu card getting crammed with all of those regular GPUs working 24/7, and you get the idea of where this nickname came from.
These cards also had loud coil whine and fan noise, so a common comment is that Yeston cards are "the loudest b*tches in the goblin caves (crypto mining facilities)".

comments.text: Big fan of anime-themed tech items here, too. There's quite a significant overlap between tech and anime culture (Akihabara and all that), and I would argue that young people in Asia are better educated in visual arts, which is multiplied by the competitiveness in the anime market itself, so it's not surprising to see really clean, fresh designs coming out of it. While in the West, the requirements for "manliness" means you shun any emotions (aside from those that translate to power) and pull all your design into edgy black rectangles. So I'm glad to see more expensive things getting the anime treatment - over time, it might finally shift people's perception of different aesthetics.

comments.text:
3:03 HusbanDO! Do not dare call them husbanDU!

Waifu is waifu because "fu" exists as a syllable in Japanese, and a "u" at the end is the most common "silent" vowel. But unfortunately "tu" and "du" don't really exist (they become "tsu" and "dzu", though there are some new unofficial ways to write them...), so for words ending in t or d they use to or do (like apartment = apaatomento, grand = gurando).

I mean yeah, waifu and husbando are western terms anyway, but they still follow the rules. And you've done such a great job so far with your weebery, so keep your standards high! =)
